@node intro "Introduction.."

  @{fg shine}@{b}Intro
  ~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   This is a GUI for some compressed audio encoders, decoders
   and players.

   It's a program that is very easy to use and that internally
   will execute your selected audio codec.
   You can add many files to a list and encode, decode or play
   all files at one time.

   The list also has a nice estimated-time-left and a nice
   ID3-tag editor with online FreeCD and CDDB capability!
   Try it out!

   You can also hide both the GUI and the output to make the
   encoding totally invisible!


@endnode

@node install "Installation.."

  @{fg shine}@{b}Installation
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   @{b}1>@{ub} Make sure MUI is installed in your system.

   @{b}2>@{ub} Copy CodeAudio somewhere in your system.

   @{b}3>@{ub} Set the paths and names for every encoder in the prefs
      to the actual location where you have your encoders in
      your system.

      Lame can be downloaded automatically by CodeAudio if you like
      it to. Executables for all systems (AmigaOS 3.x 68k, AmigaOS 4.x PPC
      including a special Altivec version, MorphOS PPC and WarpOS PPC)
      except for PowerUP are available.

      You @{u}might@{uu} have to add RunElf or similar in the beginning
      of the path(s) if you're using .elf PPC encoders.
      Example: "C:Runelf Music:encoders/ncode.elf"
      to get the PowerUP version of Ncode to work f.ex.
      But do not add "Run" as the encoders are executed asynchronous
      anyway and CodeAudio would get really confused if you do that.

   @{b}4>@{ub} Use the Easy register to registrate CodeAudio and
      send me an e-mail with the request for a keyfile (it's free).
      Also do not forget to enter your name somewhere in the registration.
      @{i}@{u}I cannot create a keyfile if you don't send me your name@{uu}
      @{u}or similar!!@{uu} @{ui}

   @{b}5>@{ub} Place the keyfile you will get in S:, ENVARC:, or the same
      directory as CodeAudio itself.


@endnode

@node reg "Registration.."

  @{fg shine}@{b}Registration
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   CodeAudio is Key-mail ware which means that you have to send
   me an e-mail with your name to get a keyfile so you can get rid
   of all annoying requesters and text!

   One registration is enough for all three version of CodeAudio.

     @{fg fill}Please use the @{u}Easy registering..@{uu} in the menu
     or when the program starts!    Thanks.@{fg text}

   It's absolutely free, I just want to know how many cool
   users I've got :-)
   Your name will of course not be used for anything else
   than to create your personal keyfile which will be sent
   back to you as soon as possible.

   So send @{"me" link auth} an e-mail at daniel@onyxsoft.se and please don't forget
   to supply your name or some other string that you want in you
   registration.

    Thankyou!


@endnode

@node req "Requirements..."

  @{fg shine}@{b}Requirements
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   OS version 37+
   MusicIn, Pegase, Ncode, MP3Enc, Lame 3, BladeEnc, Flac, OggEnc,
   OggDec, Ogg123 or Mpega

   MUI - Magical User Inteface
   TextEditor.mcc - MUI Custom Class
   BetterString.mcc - MUI Custom Class

   These are not required but recommended:
     asl.library v38+       -> if you want to be able to use a file-requester
     utility.library v33+   -> if you want log-time or delete-after-encode
     A CD-ROM file system that can list audio tracks as plain files.


@endnode

@node litelame "About CodeAudio Lite & Lame..."

  @{fg shine}@{b}Lite & Lame
  ~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   @{u}Introduction@{uu}

     As of version 2.2+ of CodeAudio there are two new reduced
     versions.
     One version, CodeAudio Lite, is reduced to only support
     Lame and Mpega. The other version, CodeAudio Lame only
     supports Lame.

     I made the decision because most people only uses Lame as
     an encoder. All ID3-tag and list functionality is still
     present in both versions and that's why the size reduction
     isn't all that huge.
     But the Lite and Lame versions start much faster because the
     MUI GUI is less complex in those.

     These two versions does not contain the wizard.

   @{u}Usage@{uu}

     Both these new versions function the same way and has the same
     features as the original version so go ahead and read usage
     of the original CodeAudio if you need help.

     However, there are a few things that are different. First,
     the Lame version does not have a page group of encoders
     obviously as it only supports one encoder. Also editing of
     ID3-tags on already encoded files can be done directly in
     the Lame version. The Lite version still needs you to switch
     to the Mpega page to edit ID3-tags on already encoded MP3's.

     Also, both the Lite and Lame version have their own prefs
     file meaning that when you start them you will not see all
     the fancy settings you have made in the original version.
     You can however load the prefs from the original version
     into the Lite or Lame version using the menu item
     @{b}Project/Load CodeAudio settings...@{ub}.


@endnode

@node disc "Disclaimer.."

  @{fg shine}@{b}Disclaimer
  ~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   You are using this program on your own risk!

   I will not be held responsible for any damage that this
   program or any encoder, decoder or player might do to your
   system or data!


@endnode

@node usage "Usage.."

  @{fg shine}@{b}Usage
  ~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}


   The first you will see when starting CodeAudio is the MP3 encoding
   @{"wizard" link wizard} which makes it very easy to encode files or CDs into MP3 with
   ID3 tags. If you do not what to use the wizard, just close its window.

   CodeAudio has @{b}a lot@{ub} of settings, most of them however is
   specific for each and every encoder and I will not go in on these
   settings. You will have to read the corresponding documentations
   for these encoders.

   If you are new to the concept of "MP3" and how to make such files
   you might also want to read a little about it on the Internet to
   get some fundamental knowledge of the words "bitrate", "layer",
   "frequency" and so on :-)

   You should know that all settings, including encoders own settings
   and ID3-editing is possible when the encoding process is running!!
   The changes will take effect when the next file starts to encode
   (if you're using a list), otherwise nothing will happen until you
   manually start a new encoding.


    @{" Wizard         " link wizard} -> Usage of the Wizard.
    @{" Main window    " link usage 37} -> Gadgets in the main window except for the encoders.
    @{" Preferences    " link usage 79} -> Settings for the program itself.
    @{" File List      " link usage 257} -> The filelist window.
    @{" ID3 Tag Editor " link usage 313} -> The ID3 Tag window.

    @{" The menu       " link usage 352} -> The elements in the menu of CodeAudio.




  @{fg fill}@{u}The main window@{uu}@{fg text}

   The main window has a number of pages, one for each encoder.
   You can drop files onto this window. If you drop more than one
   file, they will appear in the list instead and
   list-mode will be activated.


    @{b}Inputfile@{ub}  - This is the file to compress if not using the list.
                 If you drop an icon onto this window, the file
                 will appear here.

    @{b}Outputfile@{ub} - This is the destination of all compressed files if
                 not using @{b}Dynamic destination@{ub}.

    @{b}List@{ub}       - Opens the file list window that you can use when encoding
                 many files after each other.

    @{b}Use list@{ub}   - Enable the list and disable the selected "Inputfile".
                 Happens automatically when you add files to the list window.

    @{b}Encode@{ub}     - Executes the encoder with current settings.
                 Now is a good idea to put on a large pot of coffee
                 and start a good movie, unless you have a PPC, then
                 you will only have time for the coffee ;-)

    @{b}Stop@{ub}       - Stop the list. CodeAudio sends Ctrl-C|D|E|F to the
                 current encoder in progress and stops the list.

    @{b}Break@{ub}      - This will stop the current encoding process by sending
                 a Ctrl-C|D|E|F to it. A list will continue with the
                 next song though. Use Stop to stop the list completly.

    @{b}Prefs@{ub}      - Opens the preferences window.

    @{b}Quit@{ub}       - Exit the program.


   For all other settings which are different for the different encoders,
   you have to refer to the corresponding documentation.


  @{fg fill}@{u}Prefs@{uu}@{fg text}

     @{fg shine}Text output@{fg text} - Enter the output to which you want the encoders to
                   print text to. You can also specify a file here if you
                   want to log what's happening. But then you should select
                   'Errors through requester' as error-messages usually is
                   sent to the text output too.

     @{b}Disable encoder output@{ub}
       If you select this then all console output from the encoders will
       be redirected to NIL: instead of the Text output.

     @{b}Open@{ub}    - Open the text output if it is closed.
     @{b}Close@{ub}   - Close the text output if it is opened.
     @{b}Default@{ub} - Sets the text output to default.

      @{b}** Important about the Text output!! **@{ub}

       If you set this output to a file like "dh0:bla/output.log" you must
       be sure to exit the program, close the output or change back to
       a console (by f.ex pressing Default in the Text output: string)
       or your harddisk might take a trip to the validation-land!!
       (unless you're using the great PFS as I am :-))


    @{b}Stacksize@{ub}        - Select which encoder you want to change the
                       stacksize for and you can change it if you have to.

    @{b}Path@{ub}             - Path to the selected encoder.

    @{b}Delay between files@{ub} - Here you can set a delay that CodeAudio
                       should wait before it starts to encode the next file
                       in the list. This is to let the filesystem get time to
                       save the directory structure so that you wouldn't
                       loose any of your already encoded files in case of
                       a crash.
                       The delay for FFS is apx 0.5 sec and for PFS 2 sec.

    @{b}Encode-pri@{ub}       - The priority of the encoder. Don't set this to
                       something higher than `0' unless you use WarpOS or
                       PowerUP or your system might freeze until the encoding
                       is finished!

                       Mpega only allows priorities between -30 and 30 so
                       anything beyond this will be truncated to -30 or 30.

                       BladeEnc have only 6 different priority steps: IDLE,
                       LOWEST, LOWER, NORMAL, HIGHER and HIGHEST. These will
                       substitute the priorities -3, -2, -1, 0, 1 and 2.

    @{b}Ctrl-break flags@{ub} - Here you can select which flags you want to send
                       to the running encoder to make it stop.

    @{b}CD Device@{ub}        - Here you can edit which DOS device you CD-ROM is
                       connected to if you use CDDB/FreeDB to retrieve
                       titles from the net.

                       The @{b}Edit@{ub} button opens a small GUI. FreeDB has some
                       additional settings which allows it to locate the
                       CD-ROM by its device name, such as CD0:.


    @{b}Filename lenght@{ub}  - This is the maximum lenght of filenames that will
                       be shown in the filelist. If a path+filename is
                       longer, it's path will be cut from the left to the
                       right leaving just the filename visible as long as
                       possible.

    @{b}No paths@{ub}         - This will make only the filenames visible
                       in the file list window.

    @{b}No sizes@{ub}         - This will hide the size column in the file
                       list window.

    @{b}No ID3's@{ub}         - This will hide the ID3 tag column in the file
                       list window. Note! Hiding this column does @{b}not@{ub}
                       mean that ID3-tagging is disabled! If you
                       f.ex doubleclick a file with this column
                       hidden you will still tag that file.


    @{b}Open the Wizard on startup@{ub}
      Select this if you like the Wizard to open when CodeAudio is
      started.

    @{b}Check for updates on startup@{ub}
      With this enable CodeAudio will connect to the net, if a TCP/IP-
      stack is running, and check to see if there is any new version
      available for immediate download. If a new version is found you
      will be notified and offered the choise to view the changes and
      to download the update. If no update is available nothing will happen.

      You only need to disable this check if you experience problem with
      the sub process being busy after startup. This may be due to a
      slow or faulty connection to the Internet or because it is the year
      2025 and CodeAudio has stopped being developed and the server
      has moved ;)

    @{b}Look for CD device on startup@{ub}
      If no CD device is configured, CodeAudio will search your system
      for a CD drive. This is necessary to be able to add a CD in the
      wizard. However, it might cause problems, therefore it can be
      switched off here.

    @{b}Autoload ID3-tags in Mpega page@{ub}
      If you have this selected then CodeAudio will try to read the
      ID3-tags from all files that is added to the list (except if you
      load a list with ID3-tags in it) if you are at the Mpega page.

    @{b}Limit ID3-Track slider to 20@{ub}
      Sometimes you might get frustrated when trying to set the track-
      number with the slider in the ID3-tag editor. When this checkmark
      is activated the slider will only reach to 20 instead of 255 and
      it becomes much easier to control with the mouse.

    @{b}Limit ID3 length to 30 chars (ID3v1)@{ub}
      This will make the ID3 tag editor to refuse strings that is
      longer than 30 characters. 30 chars is the limit for ID3v1 tags
      anyway. Only Lame supports ID3v2 tags which use long strings.


    @{b}Dynamic destination for the list@{ub}
      If you do not want all files to end up in the same drawer then
      you can select this and the MP3-files will end up in the same
      drawer as their source-files when using the list.

    @{b}Errors through requester@{ub}
      If you select this, error messages will be displayed using a
      requester instead of printing them to the text output.

    @{b}Hide main window when encoding@{ub}
      This will hide the main window whenever a file/list is encoded.
      - So why not use MUI's iconify??
      - Because then all windows will be closed and that might not
      really be what you wanted, especially not when encoding a list
      as a progress report then is printed into the file list window.
      However, if you close all windows the application will be iconified.


    @{b}Popup finished-requester@{ub}
      Will popup a requester when a file, or your list has been finished.
      It will not pop up after every file if you are encoding a list.

    @{b}Flash screen and boing@{ub}
      Will make a DisplayBeep() (boing/flash) when a file has been
      finished. This goes for every file in a list.

    @{b}Flash power-LED@{ub}
      When this is enabled the power-LED will flash 5 times after a
      list has finished. Of course this only works on Classic Amigas.

    @{b}Automatically rename a tagged file@{ub}
      Enable this to make make CodeAudio automatically rename you mp3
      files to sensible names based on the ID3 tags of the files.

      Only files which you have made ID3 tags for can be automatically
      renamed.

      This is the same setting as the menu option "Automatically rename files"
      but it was copied into the prefs window since few users found it
      in the menu :)

    @{b}Delete source-file@{ub}
      Will delete the sourcefile when it has been finished if
      the compression took more than 20 seconds which would indicate
      that an error didn't occur at the beginning of the encoding!

    @{b}Print start and stoptime@{ub}
      Print start and stop time for every file, and the whole list
      if used, to the output.

    @{b}Save@{ub}  - This will save all settings for the whole program.
    @{b}About@{ub} - This opens the about window showing version, general
            info and who this program is registrated to.
    @{b}Close@{ub} - Close the preferences window.



  @{fg fill}@{u}List@{uu}@{fg text}

    This is the list where you can add many files that you want
    to compress in one go.
    The lister also has drag'n'drop so that you can drag and place
    the files in the order you want them compressed.

    You can also drop icons on the lister to add them that way.

    If you double-click on a file in the list it will get an ID3-tag
    associated with it, similar as pressing @{b}I-Tag@{ub}.

     @{b}Approx time left@{ub}
       If you are encoding a list then this will show the approximate
       time left until the list is finished. Note that the time is
       not accurate until one file has finished encoding. When the
       first file is encoding, the time left is based upon the assumption
       that you are encoding 16 bit stereo samples in 44.1kHz and that
       the encoder encodes in realtime, ie. time factor 1:1.

       If the encoding is slower than the estimate the time will stop
       and the gauge will alternate between the last and second last
       position until the file is finished and a new more accurate
       estimation can be done for the next file.

       If the time factor differs more than 8% when the encoding has
       finished from the time factor when the encoding started you will
       be asked to save the prefs. Do that so that you will get accurate
       time prediction for all files next time you encode!

     @{b}Add@{ub}   - Add file(s) to the list.
     @{b}CD@{ub}    - Add a complete audio CD to the list.
             This only works if you have an audio CD in you CR-ROM drive
             and the CD file system can list audio tracks as files.
     @{b}Rem@{ub}   - Remove the selected file(s) from the list.
     @{b}Clr@{ub}   - Clear the whole list.
     @{b}Load@{ub}  - Load a previously saved list from disk.
     @{b}Save@{ub}  - Save a list to disk so that you can edit the ID3-tags later
             again if you want. The list is in text format.
     @{b}G-Tag@{ub} - Group Tag: Set the same ID3-tag to all the selected files in the list.
             If you tag many files from the same album or that has the
             same artist it is preferable to first use this, then you
             only have to change the common values on one file and the
             other one will also get the same values as they have the
             same tag. Then use @{b}I-Tag@{ub} to set individual tags
             on the same file, they will then remember the old values.
     @{b}I-Tag@{ub} - Set individual ID3-tag(s) to the selected file(s) in the
             list. If you tag an album it is easier to first set a
             group-tag and set Album, Year and so, then use this
             to set the Titles and perhaps Artists if it's a collection.
             If the file has no tag when you press this the file will
             be searched for a tag and read it if it has one.
     @{b}UnTag@{ub} - Remove ID3-tag(s) from the selected file(s) in the list.



  @{fg fill}@{u}ID3 Tag Editor@{uu}@{fg text}

    In this window you can insert information you want in the ID3 tag
    of your MP3-files. Currently only Ncode and Lame support this
    natively but you can use it with every encoder anyway because if
    an encoder other than the above is use CodeAudio will set
    the tags instead.

    In the prefs there is switch that you can uncheck to make this
    ID3 tag editor handle strings longer than 30 characters which is
    otherwise maximum for ID3v1 tags. This is possible because Lame
    has the ability to write ID3v2 tags.

    @{b}Title@{ub}    - The Title-field of the ID3-Tag.
    @{b}Artist@{ub}   - The Artist-field of the ID3-Tag.
    @{b}Album@{ub}    - The Album-field of the ID3-Tag.
    @{b}Year@{ub}     - The Year-field of the ID3-Tag.
    @{b}Comment@{ub}  - The Comment-field of the ID3-Tag.
    @{b}Genre@{ub}    - The Genre of the music.
    @{b}Track no@{ub} - If this song came from a CD, this is the track
               number of the song on the CD.
               If you use this (i.e. set it to a non-zero value)
               you will get an ID3v1.1 tag instead of a normal
               ID3v1.0 tag. This is displayed at the top of the window.

    @{b}Get@{ub}   - Get the ID3 tag of the current selected MP3('s).
            This is only possible when the Mpega page is active.
            To get the ID3's for all files in a list there is a menu
            option in the Managing menu.

    @{b}Set@{ub}   - Set the ID3 tag of the current selected MP3('s).
            This is only possible when the Mpega page is active.
            To set the ID3's for all files in a list there is a menu
            option in the Managing menu.

    @{b}Close@{ub} - Closes the window.



  @{fg fill}@{u}The menus@{uu}@{fg text}

   The menu of CodeAudio is the same for all windows.
   It contains common things like console-control and access
   to preferences and so..

   @{b}@{u}Project@{uu}@{ub}

     @{b}Open file list window...@{ub}
       This will open the filelist window.

     @{b}Open ID3 Tag Editor...@{ub}
       This will open the ID3 Tag Editor window.

     @{b}Open the Wizard...@{ub}
       The wizard normally opens when CodeAudio is started but if it
       was closed it can be reopened here.

     @{b}Preferences...@{ub}
       This will open the preferences window.

     @{b}Load settings@{ub}
       This will reload all settings.

     @{b}Save settings@{ub}
       This will save all settings. It's the same as pressing "Save" in
       the prefs window.

     @{b}Load settings from...@{ub}
       This will open an ASL-requester and let you load any prefs file
       you want that you have previously saved.

       Useful if you like to import the settings from for example
       TheMpegEndGUI Lite into TheMpegEndGUI Lame, or anything similar.

     @{b}Save settings as...@{ub}
       This will open an ASL-requester and let you save your setting
       anywhere you want.

     @{b}About@{ub}
       This will open the about-requester which also contain information
       about your registration.

     @{b}OnyxSoft@{ub}
       Shows some info about our, still "virtual" company :)

     @{b}Easy register@{ub}
       If you choose this, a few lines will be printed to the text output
       which you then can copy into your e-mail program and send to me.
       Use this if you're too lazy to write an e-mail yourself ;-)

     @{b}MUI settings..@{ub}
       This will open the standard MUI settings window for CodeAudio.

     @{b}Quit@{ub}
       This will quit the program.


   @{b}@{u}Managing@{uu}@{ub}

     @{b}Encode/Play@{ub}
       This will start encoding if an encoder page, such as Lame, is active,
       or start playing if a player page, such as Mpega, is active.

     @{u}Stop@{uu}

       @{b}Break the current encoder@{ub}
         This will send a Ctrl-C|D|E|F to the current encoder in progress.

       @{b}Stop list at next@{ub}
         This will make the list stop after the current encoding process
         is finished.

       @{b}Stop list now@{ub}
         This will send a Ctrl-C|D|E|F to the current encoder in progress
         and then stop the list.

     @{b}Print commandline(s)@{ub}
       This will print the commandline(s) that is usually supplied to
       the encoder to the text output instead.

     @{b}Default values for this de/encoder@{ub}
       Revert all settings to default for the current encoder/decoder/player.

     @{b}Reset all encode/play factors@{ub}
       This will set the factor variables to the default values.
       The factor variables is used to calculate the remaining time it
       will take to finish a list or a file. See "Approx time left" in
       the List section of this guide for more info.

     @{b}Rescan file lengths in the list@{ub}
        In case some of your files that you currently have in the list have
        changed this might be useful to make time prediction more accurate.


     @{u}Main window@{uu}

       @{b}Open Main window..@{ub}
         This will open the Main window during encoding if it has been closed.

       @{b}Close Main window..@{ub}
         This will close the Main window during encoding if it is open.

     @{u}Text output@{uu}

       @{b}Open output@{ub}
         This will open the text output if it is closed.

       @{b}Close output@{ub}
         This will close the text output if it is opened.

       @{b}Clear console@{ub}
         This will clear the text output if it's a console window, by
         writing ASCII-12 to it.

     @{b}Check for update for CodeAudio@{ub}
        Normally The..GUI checks for new versions at startup but if you
        would like to check manually, if you were not online when starting
        The..GUI, then you can use this.

        Nothing will be installed immediately, you will be asked first.
        After the update a new directory called "OldVersions" should
        have been created and the old versions moved into it so you can
        restore the last version if you didn't like the new version.

     @{b}Download and install Lame@{ub}
        Use this if you would like to install Lame, or install another
        version. The..GUI will give you a list of available versions of
        Lame. You then double-click on the version you would like to
        install and it will be downloaded and installed and the preferences
        (the path) will be updated accordingly.

        The downloaded executables will be placed in a directory called "Bin".

     @{b}Download and install CDDB@{ub}
        If you try to use CDDB without have it installed you will be given
        the opportunity to install it immediately, but if you would like
        to give it a try manually you can use this option.

        The CDDB package consists of two libraries which will be placed
        in a directory called "Libs". Another directory called "CDDB"
        will be created and the assign "CDDB:" set to it on-the-fly.

     @{b}Download and install FreeDB@{ub}
        If you try to use FreeDB without have it installed you will be given
        the opportunity to install it immediately, but if you would like
        to give it a try manually you can use this option.

        The FreeDB package will be downloaded as and lha archive since it
        contains a number of components. Lha must therefore be in your
        path to be able to extract the archive. All parts of FreeDB will
        be installed in a directory called "Libs" and "FreeDB", both of
        which will be placed in the directory of CodeAudio itself.

     @{b}Uninstall CDDB@{ub}
        Offers the possibility to uninstall CDDB from your CodeAudio
        directory. It is not possible to uninstall CDDB if it was installed
        somewhere else in your system.

     @{b}Uninstall FreeDB@{ub}
        Offers the possibility to uninstall FreeDB from your CodeAudio
        directory. It is not possible to uninstall FreeDB if it was installed
        somewhere else in your system.


   @{b}@{u}Encoders@{uu}@{ub}

     This will flip the GUI to the encoder/player's page you selected
     in this menu.


   @{b}@{u}ID3-tagging@{uu}@{ub}

     @{u}For all selected files..:@{uu}
       These actions will only take place for files that already have a
       tag in the list. Double-click a file to create a tag, or select
       many files and click I-Tag (I for individual) to create tags for
       the files.

       @{b}Set filename to Title@{ub}
         This will remove the extension from the filename and ask you
         to remove leading numbers in the filenames if any are found
         and then copy the filename to the Title-field if the ID3-tag.
         This function only affects selected files in the list.

       @{b}Set filename to both Title and Artist@{ub}
         If you have filenames like this f.ex:
         "The artist - The song title.mp3"
         you can use this to split the filename by the " - " so that
         the first part of the filename goes to the Artist field and
         the second part to the Title field in the ID3-tag. If the
         filename does not have a " - " combination a single "-" will
         be search for instead. If none is found the Artist will be
         empty. The extension and leading number, if any found and
         after asking you, will be removed before the filename is
         copied to the fields.
         This function only affects selected files in the list.

       @{b}Set directory name as Artist@{ub}
         This will get the parent directory name and set it to the
         Artist field. If you have a path like this:
         "Music:MP3/2-Unlimited/The Real Thing.mp3"
         then the Artist field will be set to "2-Unlimited".
         This function only affects selected files in the list.

       @{b}Set directory name as Album@{ub}
         Same as above but the directory name will be set to the
         Album-field instead.

       @{b}Set beginning of filename as track number@{ub}
         If you have filenames like this:
         "08.Hardworld - Dreamgarden.mp3", ie. it starts with a number
         you can use this to get this number set to the Track field of
         the ID3v1.1 tag.
         This function only affects selected files in the list.

       @{b}Generate track numbers@{ub}
         Will generate track numbers starting with the track number of
         the first selected file, if it has a number, otherwise it
         starts with number 1.

       @{b}Set filecomment to ID3-Comment@{ub}
         This will try to get the filecomment of each file and set it
         to the ID3-Comment field.
         This function only affects selected files in the list.


     @{b}Automatically rename files@{ub}
       Enable this if you would like your encoded files to be automatically
       renamed according to a template string based on the ID3-tags.

     @{b}Rename automatically now@{ub}
       If you forgot to set the switch @{b}Automatically rename files@{ub} or you
       have added files previously encoded you can perform the rename
       directly by using this option.

     @{b}Edit rename format string...@{ub}
       In this window you edit the auto rename format string.
       Placeholders (%%x) are used to insert elements from the ID3-tag
       of each particular file, where 'x' is replaced by the letters
       t, a, l, y, c, g, n, o, e for title, Artist, Album, Year, Comment,
       Genre, Track number, Original filename and file extension.


     @{b}Get ID3-tags from all files@{ub}
       This will read the ID3-tag from all MP3-files in the list.
       This only works when the Mpega page is active.

     @{b}Set the ID3-tags to all files@{ub}
       This will write an ID3-tag to all files in the list that has a tag.
       This only works when the Mpega page is active.

     @{b}UnTag all files in the list@{ub}
       This will remove the tag from all files in the list.
       Note: The tag will not be removed from the files, only deactivated
       in the list. This is the same a the button UnTag but for all files,
       not only selected ones.

     @{b}Import a CDDB-file...@{ub}
       This will let you select a file from an ASL-requester which should
       be a CDDB-file of some kind. In CDDB these files lie in the
       @{i}Read_DiscIDs/ @{ui}directory and has names such as DiscID_0xAE12590C.
       In ACDB these files can be found in the @{i}disks/ @{ui} directory and
       are called something like ID1600A8D9047EA3.

       Both the CDDB and ACDB packages can be found on Aminet.

       When importing a CDDB-file the ID3-fields Title, Artist, Album and Track
       and possibly Commend will be set. This means that you can manually set a
       group-tag (G-Tag) on all files in you album and set the Year, default
       Comment and Genre fields before you import a CDDB-file so you don't have
       to do it on every file later.
       All files (as far as the CDDB-file goes) will get individual tags (I-Tag)
       after the import.

       The CDDB-file will be imported to the files from the top of the file lister
       and down as far as there are lines in the CDDB-file or files in the lister
       in CodeAudio. Make sure your files in the lister are in the right order
       before you import. Use drag'n'drop to rearrange you files so that track 1
       is the first one in the list.

       The format of a CDDB-file is something like this:

         Artist
         Album [time]
         Tracknum1 - Artist1 / Title1 (Remix comment1) [time1]
         Tracknum2 - Artist2 / Title2 (Remix comment2) [time2]
         Tracknum3 - Artist3 / Title3 (Remix comment3) [time3]
         .....
         ...

       The first line contains the artist. If it is some sort of various artists
       collection album this probably says "div" or "Various Artists". It will
       not be used if the track itself has an artist field, which it usually do
       on various collections.

       The second line contains the name of the album and possibly the total
       time of it. The time will be stripped and the album line will be copied
       directly to the Album field of the ID3-tag for each file.

       The third and every following lines are the tracks. They may contain a
       track-number in the beginning. If it does, this will be copied to the
       Track field of the ID3 and stripped from the rest of the line. If it has
       no track number, the Track field in the ID3-tag will be set by a line-
       counter starting at 1 for the first track.

       Each track may have it's own artist. If it does, it will be set to the
       Artist field of the ID3-tag. If there is no artist in the track the global
       artist from line 1 will be used instead.
       If the tracks have a time field, this will be removed and the title part
       will be copied to the Title field of the ID3-tag.
       If a track has both artist and title they are separated by a slash (/) or
       a dash (-). If there is no slash or dash in the track the whole line,
       minus tracknum and time, will be taken as the title of the track.

       I there is a parentheses at the end of the title this will be parsed.
       If the track has an artist the parenthesis will be set to the Comment
       field of the ID3-tag. If the track doesn't have a artist, the parenthesis
       will be set as the Artist @{u}unless@{uu} it contains the word "mix" or
       "edit". In that case it will be set to the Comment instead and the Artist
       field will be set by the global artist from line 1.

       Example 1 of a CDDB-file with all fields:

         Various Artists
         Disney's The Lion King Collection [65:27]
         01 - Tina Turner / He lives in you (Original mix) [4:43]
         02 - Elton John / Circle of life (radio edit) [4:52]
         03 - Instrumental / This Land (long version) [2:55]


       Example 2 with only basic fields:

         div
         Tekno Magazine Music
         Flow
         Runnin'
         Stranded


       Example 3, an alternative file (my debug and test file :)):

         Various Artists
         Rave Mission 07 - CD2 [75:10]
         Secret- Love (grej edita) [08:38]
         17-Aqualoop / Twilight Zone [05:22]
         123 - E-Space / Trance Research (comment) [05:57]
         DJ Randy - Erotmania [06:02]
         Nostrum-Baby (Original) [08:15]
         hej och hĺ (artistus) [08:15]



     @{b}Obtain CDDB for a CD@{ub}
       This will try to read the CDID from the Audio-CD you have
       inserted into your CD-reader. It will then use cddb.library
       to try to obtain the title, artist and other info for this
       CD, either over the net or from CDDB: if you already have
       used another tool to read the data from the Internet.

       If all goes well a window with the tracks that was found
       will be displayed in a list so that you can see that all
       is allright before you press Accept. It is also possible to
       remove tracks you do not want in case you are only encoding
       a few songs for example.

       If something went wrong a window will open with some info
       about the error and a "Try again" button. There is also
       a "More"-button you can press to see exactly what function
       in cdplay- or cddb.library that caused the error.
       Usually you get an error if a CD is not inserted or busy
       at the moment.

     @{b}Obtain FreeDB for a CD@{ub}
       Performs the same actions as for CDDB (see above), but
       uses freedb.library instead which connects to another
       site on the Internet that may have other CD titles.

       FreeDB supports multiple targets but CodeAudio currently
       unfortunately can only list the first CD found.


@endnode

@node wizard "The Wizard"

  @{fg shine}@{b}The Wizard
  ~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   From v3.0 CodeAudio features an MP3 encoding wizard which will
   greatly help you to quickly create high-quality MP3 encodings using
   Lame as the encoder.

   Features:
   * Can automatically locate your CD-ROM drive and add the audio tracks
     from an audio CD to the list of files to encode. It requires that the
     CD file system can list tracks as DOS readable files though.

   * Will detect the presence of Lame and offer to download it if it
     couldn't be found.

   * Will automatically try to access FreeDB or CDDB (in that order)
     to retrieve artist and title info etc. from the Internet if you
     have inserted an audio CD to be encoded.

   * Will offer to download FreeDB or CDDB if none of them could be found.

   * Lets you manually select FreeDB or CDDB as source for the album
     information and lets you edit the ID3 tags for each file.

   * Shows a preview of the new filenames and renames the files
     automatically after encoding.


   @{u}Usage@{uu}

   The wizard has seven pages from the beginning to the end. All pages
   should be fairly self-explaning (which is the whole point of a wizard).
   If your are in any doubt, the Help window should give you a simple
   explanation as well as supply extra information about various parts.

   You can close the wizard using the normal window close gadget at
   anytime but all settings and files you may have added will be
   forgotten and the normal expert GUI of CodeAudio will open. The
   wizard can be reopened from the expert GUI using the menu option
   "Project->Open the Wizard..." and it will always open on the first
   page.

   Following is a description of each page and what happens when you
   click the Next» or «Back buttons.

   @{b}Welcome to the Wizard! (1/7)@{ub}

      This is the introduction page. It gives a brief overview of the
      features that lies ahead.

      If you would like to encode an audio CD, this is the time to
      insert the CD into your CD-ROM. You should wait until the system
      has recognized the CD and is showing an icon on Workbench. When
      the CD is recognized you can press Next» to go to the next page
      which shows a list of files to be encoded.

      When clicking Next» the wizard will attempt to read the CD that
      is configured in the preferences. If it fails to read this CD it
      will scan the system for another CD. If it finds one it will try
      to read the tracks on it as files and add them to the list on
      page 2.

      It may fail to read the CD for a number of reasons, the most
      common is that your CD file system cannot show an audio CD as a
      DOS disc with audio files on it. Nothing to be done about that.
      You will have to use another tool to leech the tracks down to
      harddisk and then use the wizard to encode the files. @{b}Note@{ub}
      though that you should leave the CD in the drive because you
      can still use FreeDB or CDDB to get album information from the
      Internet using the Wizard!

   @{b}Select files to turn into MP3 (2/7)@{ub}

      This page shows a list of all files to be encoded. An audio CD
      may have been added automatically. If not, you can try clicking
      "Add CD" and the wizard will search for and try to read a CD to
      add the tracks to the list.

      You can of course also add other files using the "Add Files"
      button. It is also possible to drag'n'drop files or a directory
      from Workbench onto the wizard window and the files will be
      added.

      Clicking «Back will not clear the list. The files will still
      be here when you click Next» again.

      Clicking Next» will again verify the files in the list to see
      if any of them have been manually added from an audio CD. The
      wizard will remember this.

   @{b}Time (3/7)@{ub}

      This pages asks you if you are in a hurry. You can answer Yes
      or No. Default is always No.

      Leaving the default option of No when clicking Next» brings you
      to the next page where you get to select encoding quality.

      Selecting Yes will turn the Next» button into a Start button
      and it will not be possible to set any specific quality settings.
      A low quality 128kbps encoding will be chosen and the ID3 tag
      editing and FreeDB/CDDB access will be skipped.

      The output path for the encoded files will be automatically
      chosen to be the same directory as the source files, except
      if the files are directly from an audio CD. In this case the
      output MP3 files will be stored in a local directory by default
      called OutputFiles in the directory CodeAudio is installed.

      Clicking "Start!" will immediately start the encoding process.

   @{b}Encoding Quality (4/7)@{ub}

      This page lets you select the quality of your files.

      You should base your decision on your listening equipment.
      - Do you have a high-end HiFi system, or just some crappy
      PC-speakers? Perhaps you have something in between, an average
      stereo equipment, with average quality speakers?

      Also base your decision on your diskspace requirement.
      - How much storage space are your files allowed to take?
      Do you plan on using them in an MP3 player with limited storage
      capability?
      The Extra High quality setting takes at least twice as much
      storage space as the Low quality setting, yet most people
      cannot tell the difference in quality when played on their
      own average or low-quality stereo equipment!!

      These are the quality settings offered:
      @{b}Extra Low@{ub} - 40kbps, 22kHz Mono, high quality (-h) switch
        This creates very low quality encodings and should not
        normally be used for any normal music that you plan on
        listening to in anything better than the speaker of a mobile
        phone or a toy or something.

      @{b}Low@{ub} - 128kbps, Joint-Stereo
        This is now considered low quality but is really not very bad
        at all for average music in average equipment. There is a
        dullness though. The sound is not as rich in detail and treble
        as the original @{i}might @{ui}have been.

      @{b}Medium@{ub} - 160kbps ABR by the --preset hifi switch, -h switch
        Creates a good quality encoding without wasting too many
        bits. I can personaly not hear the difference between this
        setting and an original encoding. Especially not for normal
        compressed pop or electronic music.

      @{b}High@{ub} - VBR with -V2 quality setting
        This creates really high quality encodings using the VBR mode
        of Lame which distributes the bits where they are most needed
        removing those artifacts that can otherwise be heard in a few
        places in some songs with lower quality, especially CBR (constant
        bitrate) encodings.

      @{b}Extra High@{ub} - VBR with the --preset extreme switch
        This switch uses a preset switch tuned for extra high quality
        also using VBR. The file size when encoding with this setting
        is about twice the size of the Low quality setting. Still, you
        will probably find it difficult to hear the difference :-)

      @{b}Custom@{ub} - No settings will be changed. The saved, or last
        used preferences (which may be another of the above settings)
        will be used as they are. Do not use this unless you have some
        special settings you like to use, or if you like to encode using
        the absolute defaults of Lame for example.


      @{b}Clear custom settings@{ub}
        This button will set all setting of Lame to the default values.
        It may be necessary to do this if you have made some incompatible
        quality settings or if you enable the decode option or something
        like that for Lame. In that case the wizard could produce a very
        unexpected result.

      @{b}Show the encoder output in a console window@{ub}
        This is the same, but inversed, functionality of the setting
        "Disable encoder output" that you can make in the preferences
        section.

        Selecting this option will cause the console window to open when
        the encoding process is started and you will see the encoder,
        Lame, in action. If something goes wrong it may help to go back
        and set this flag so you can see the actual error message that
        Lame may output in the console window.

      When you click Next» on this page the wizard will try to contact
      FreeDB to retireve album information if the tracks were taken from
      an audio CD. If FreeDB is not found, the wizard will attempt to
      contact CDDB instead. If CDDB is not installed either you will be
      asked if you like to download and install FreeDB. If you decline
      it will ask if you like to download and install CDDB instead.

      If you choose to download and install any of FreeDB or CDDB, it
      will immediately be installed but the wizard will not attempt to
      read any of FreeDB or CDDB again. This will be up to you on the
      next page.

   @{b}MP3 File Information - ID3 Tags (5/7)@{ub}

      @{b}Get CDDB.com@{ub} / @{b}Get FreeDB.com@{ub}
        This is the page where it is possible to manually retrieve FreeDB
        or CDDB information from the Internet by a click on a button.
        Remember that you need to have the CD in question in your CD-ROM
        for this to work, even if the wizard could not read the actual
        tracks itself from the CD. You can read FreeDB or CDDB as many
        times you like.

      @{b}Output path@{ub} / @{b}Automatic@{ub}
        At the top of the page you can see the path where the MP3 files
        will be stored. If the area is ghosted and the Automatic flag is
        set the files will be stored in the same place the source files,
        unless the source files are audio CD tracks. In that case the
        path that can be seen behind the ghosted area will be used.

        You can deactivate the automatic path at any time and select
        another specific place for your files. All files will then be
        stored in this location.

        If you change the Output Path you can save it by using the menu
        option "Project/Save settings".

        One level of directory can be created automatically. The wizard
        will even try to find a directory icon to copy for this output
        directory, even if it is automatically selected by the wizard
        or not.

        If an audio CD is encoded and FreeDB or CDDB information was
        retrieved such that the first file in the list will have an Album
        set for its ID3 tag, this Album will be used as a directory to
        store the output MP3 files in.

      @{b}Make Tag@{ub} / @{b}Clear tag@{ub}
        If other files than an audio CD are to be encoded, or if there
        was no FreeDB or CDDB information available, you can make and
        edit ID3 tags of your own. Mark a file in the list and click
        "Make Tag" to enable the tag field.

        It is now possible to fill in the title, artist, etc. manually.
        If you hit Enter in any of the ID3 tag fields you will be given
        the choise to have this value copied for all files in the list.

        @{b}+@{ub}
        The Genre has a button with a '+' symbol to copy the genre for
        all files in the list since there is no field to hit Enter in.

      @{u}Editing the file renaming scheme@{uu}

      If a file has an ID3 tag it will be renamed after being encoded.
      The format pattern for how the files should be renamed defaults
      to <track number>-<artist> - <title>.<extension> but can be
      edited by chosing the menu option
        "Managing->Edit rename format string..."
      The format string consists of switches, or placeholders. One
      %<character> for each of title, artist, album etc. The window
      is rather self-explanatory.


      Up to this point it is still possible to click «Back all the way
      to the first page of the wizard. If you however were to replace
      the files on the second page, all ID3 tag settings you have made
      will be lost and you need to start over when coming forward to
      this page, page 5, again.

      The Next» button has now turned into a "Start!" button and pressing
      it will start encoding your tracks and renaming them to how you
      see them in the list.

   @{b}Encoding in progress (6/7)@{ub}

      This page will show you the progress of the encoding if all goes
      well. There is a gauge that shows progress for each individual file.
      The time displayed in the gauge show the total time left for all
      files. If the encoding goes slower than the gauge has estimated,
      the gauge will come to an end before a file is finished and the
      time will turn into ??:??:?? until the file has ended. The gauge
      will now have adjusted itself for the next song and should become
      more accurate.

      It is possible to close the wizard using the normal window close
      gadget during a running encoding. In this case the wizard will be
      iconified and will automatically reopen when all files have finished
      encoding.

      If there was an error during encoding, an error message is displayed
      and the "Abort" button turns into a «Back button. Clicking «Back
      now will bring you back to the last page you were at. It depends
      on if you chose that you were in a hurry or not.

      @{b}Abort@{ub}
        It is possible to abort a running encoding. You will first be
        asked if you really want to abort. If you chose to abort it
        is only possible to restart from the beginning. It is not
        possible to resume where the encoding was stopped in the list.

   @{b}Done! (7/7)@{ub}

      Have you reached this page, it means that all files have been
      encoded and possibly renamed if they were ID3 tagged.

      @{b}Finish@{ub}
        Clicking this button will exit the wizard and CodeAudio. It is
        not the same a closing the window which will instead open the
        old expert GUI.

        If the time prediction was unaccurate for the first file, a
        checkmark will probably be selected which means that the settings
        will be reloaded and then saved with the new time prediction data
        when you click "Finish".

      @{b}«««More@{ub}
        Clicking this button will bring you back to the beginning of
        the wizard and restart the whole process. Useful if you have
        mode CDs to encode.


@endnode

@node feat "Features.."

  @{fg shine}@{b}Features & History
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

 @{fg fill}* NEW *@{fg text} The wizard now offers to no longer encodes all files if some files have
         already been encoded. For example if there is an error or crash after
         encoding half a CD you don't have to encode the entire CD again to get
         the tags correct.

 @{fg fill}* NEW *@{fg text} Added a setting if CodeAudio should look for a CD at startup.
         This may speed up and prevent problems for some people when starting
         CodeAudio.

 @{fg fill}* NEW *@{fg text} Added a new encoder and player for the Amiga optimized A8 format.
         (Untested since I couldn't compile ConvertA8 or PlayA8.)

 @{fg fill}* NEW *@{fg text} Reorganized the encoders/decoders/players into groups to make it
         easier to overview.

 @{fg fill}* NEW *@{fg text} Added another tag menu option: "Generate track numbers" that will simply
         generate a number series starting with the first selected file in
         the list. (Normal mode, not wizard.)

 @{fg fill}* NEW *@{fg text} Changed the wizard Extra High mode to use stereo mode instead of j-stereo.

 @{fg fill}* NEW *@{fg text} The wizard can now create recursive target directories and will not
         create the directory/ies until encoding starts.

 @{fg fill}* FIX *@{fg text} Reorganized the main buttons in the main window to be more logical.

 @{fg fill}* FIX *@{fg text} Now using the MUIM_Application_PushMethod for all GUI actions made
         from the subtask. This should make primarily the updating but also
         encoding more stable.

 @{fg fill}* FIX *@{fg text} Reencoding a song with auto rename didn't work very well because it
         failed to rename if the file existed. Now deleting if rename fails.

 @{fg fill}* FIX *@{fg text} Fix enabling or CDDB menus When adding a CD.

@{b}v3.05@{ub} (auto-update)
 @{fg fill}**@{fg text} CodeAudio now checks the length of output filenames and warns when
    they are longer than 107 characters.

@{b}v3.04@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Dieter B. has been very kind and pulled the HTML docs up to date again!
   I will try to keep it in sync from now on.

 @{fg fill}**@{fg text} The default AHI mode ID for Mpega became "$DEFA" instead of "Default".

@{b}v3.03@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now setting the execute file protection bit after installing Lame or
   updating CodeAudio. This is needed on the JXFS file system.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed a quit issue.

@{b}v3.02@{ub} (auto-update)
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The Extra High setting in the Wizard used the standard instead of
   extreme VBR setting.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed the shell output flag in the wizard which was not synched with
   the flag in the Prefs.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added the flag MUIA_Application_UsedClasses which makes only those
   MCCs that are used to be listed in the MUI Settings.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed a wierd bug which made it necessary to sometimes click twice
   on the Finish button in the wizard.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Remove a stupid question which could pop up at the end of the wizard.

@{b}v3.01@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} ASL parameter could be inconclusive - The lister could show
    only drawers in some situations.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added the setting "Automatically rename file" also to the
    Prefs window.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now it is possible to get tracks automatically numbered when
    pressing enter in the track string in the Wizard.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The artist and album fields were swapped when hitting enter
    in a tag field in the Wizard.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Missing list redraw when setting "for all tags" in the Wizard.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The "Input file" and "Output file" always showed the file
    that was *previously* processed in the Wizard.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The file list on the ID3 tags page in the Wizard now uses
    NList.mcc which makes it possible to scroll sideways.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now there is an easier way of saving Default output path
    in the Wizard.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The buggy tasker object used for the sub process has finally
    been replaced by proper AmigaOS calls.

@{b}v3.0@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} An MP3 encoding Wizard has been added which makes it easier
    than ever before to make high quality MP3 files in no time!
 
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added support for Flac, the free lossless audio codec.
 
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Updated locale catalogs for German, Italian, Spanish
 
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Works on MorphOS with MUI 4.
 
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Restructured every encoder GUI that had more than one page
    and turned them into virtual groups.
 
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Made it possible to drop directories on the list window and
    the Wizard.
 
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Updated to the latest Lame executables for all systems on
    the auto-update server.
 
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} AutoUpdate should work in E-UAE/Linux now.
 
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Should not try to locate the CD drive at startup everytime
    now. Also enhanced the CD detection code a lot so it works
    on MorphOS and WinUAE.
 
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Better installation of FreeDB.
 
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Uninstall options for CDDB and FreeDB if they were installed
    by TheMPegEncGUI/CodeAudio.
 
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} ...and much more minor fixes and improvements all over! :-)

@{b}v2.65@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added support for faad - AAC/MP4 audio decoder.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Possibly fixed a bug when the ID3-tag limit was set to 30 characters
    but more than 30 characters was generated from CDDB/FreeDB.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Updated italian translation by Samir Hawamdeh.

@{b}v2.64@{ub} (auto-update)
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added support for FreeDB.library!
    You can choose between CDDB and FreeDB from the ID3-Tagging menu.

@{b}v2.63@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed a bug in the ObtainCDDB that said that there were less
    entries (0) in the filelist than in the CDDB.

@{b}v2.62@{ub} - AutoUpdate release
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Actions on the Mpega page got shifted into some menu options
    due to me not recompiling the Mpega module after adding the
    auto update feature in v2.60.
 
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added "Rename automatically now" to the menu so that you can
    rename existing files based on the ID3-tag, not only during
    encoding.
 
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The auto rename feature now filters out the most critically
    forbidden characters from the new filename: :/"?#`*<>
 
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added a switch to not check for updates at startup. May be of
    use if you experience problems when starting The..GUI.
    Generally you don't want or need to switch off this feature
    though since you'll miss all new updates unless you check manually
    using the menu option.
 
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} "Autoload ID3-tags in Mpega page" now also affects picking a
    single input file or typing in the input file string.
 
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The menu item "Set all the ID3-tags" didn't work. It had been
    "disconnected".
 
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The Lite version didn't set the Mpega input/output file string
    in some circumstances and also didn't update disabling in the
    tag editor when flipping page.
 
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The requester about CDDB: should not pop up when trying to
    obtain CDDB even if the assign is not setup. It should be done
    automatically now. (It was automatic before too but in the wrong
    place.)
 
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now the Help-key should bring up the guide if the guide is placed
    in the default directory PROGDIR:Docs/.
 
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Forgot to change the dates in v2.61. Good thing I implemented
    this live update :-)

@{b}v2.61@{ub} - AutoUpdate release
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added the --noreplaygain switch.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added a freetext field for newer parameters not yet present
    in the GUI.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed a possible bug in an error message during download.

@{b}v2.60@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Finally added the functionality to automatically rename files
    that have been encoded!
    See menu/ID3-tagging/Edit rename format string.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now TheMPegEncGUI can automatically download and install
    various versions of Lame and the CDDB package for you if you
    do not already have it!

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} From now on you never need to check the web for new versions
    because TheMPegEncGUI will automatically detect and give the
    opportunity to automatically download and install new versions!

@{b}v2.51@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed some problem with weight-disappearing objects in the
    list window. Something is buggy there so I removed all weigthed
    stuff..

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Missed the "Volume Scaling" group title in the translation.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed some differencies between the 68k and the PPC version
    of BladeEnc. -prio and -refresh is apparently not supported
    by BladeEnc 68k.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added the possibility to have the power-LED flash after a
    finished list on Classic machines.

@{b}v2.5@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Completely reworked the way the default parameters are
    handled! Now the "Do not exclude default values" is gone
    from the prefs and every setting has its own specific
    default or auto mode instead.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added a lot of new settings for Lame, including the new
    --replaygain-accurate which prevents newer versions of Lame
    from generating quiet MP3s. I'm not sure if it works though...?

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Menu shoutcuts didn't seem to work on OS4 (maybe they didn't
    work on other systems either?). This is now fixed. Menu
    shortcuts apparently need to be in uppercase to be accepted.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed a bug which caused a crash if you changed the console
    settings while encoding with output to the console.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Raised the stack a bit, so you who might have had trouble with
    TheMPegEncGUI crashing on OS4 might find it more reliable now.

@{b}v2.41@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} -rawbyteorder didn't work for BladeEnc. Forgot a "=".

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} When encoding single files and the time estimate finished
    early, it wouldn't reset when encoding a new single file.

@{b}v2.4@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now full CDDB-support is built-in into TheMPegEncGUI!
    You don't need to use some other program to get those CD-IDs
    from the net and then try to figure out what file it was and
    load that into The_GUI, all is now automated.
    Insert a CD, add files (previously leeched off the CD, or
    directly from the CD if you have f.ex. AllegroCDFS), then
    select Obtain CDDB from the ID3-Tag menu.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} When drag'n'dropping files into the file list window some
    menu options were not enabled. You had to add a file using
    the Add-button. Fixed.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} There were some dublettes and inconsistencies of hotkeys
    for the menues.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Switching between Lame/Mpega in Lite didn't work from the menu.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The bitrate was not correct in the full and Lite versions.

@{b}v2.31@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} I have made a new attempt to fix the enforcer hits occurring at
    startup. I'm pretty sure I did it now after a bug-report from
    a user showing me that shared global variables accessed by the
    subprocess before A4 was initialized seemed to be the cause.
    Now the subprocess' "main" handles no variables, including
    local, before A4 is retrieved.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Two commands in the Ogg123 (OggPlay) commandline had "=" signs
    in them which doesn't work with Ogg. Fixed.

@{b}v2.3@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now it's possible to import CDDB/ACDB-files automatically into
    the ID3-tags on files in the file list! (Yes I know it's not full
    automatic CDDB-support but it's one step in the right direction
    anyway :)) This means that you have to use CDDB or ACDB to download
    the descriptions for your CD's, then you can import these text-files
    in TheMPegEncGUI.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Included OggDec support into TheMPegEncGUI!
    (Translators: .cd file slightly extended)

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Included OggPlay (ogg123) support into TheMPegEncGUI!
    (Translators: .cd file slightly extended)

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} If encoding a song took longer time than TheMPegEncGUI
    expected the time counter didn't stop, as supposed in v2.23
    but continued to count every other second. Fixed.
    Now the gauge alternate between the last and second last
    position and the time stops counting and adds a ?-char.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} If you tried to set an ID3-tag on a MP3-files which had a track
    number while the "Limit ID3 length to 30 chars" was set in the
    prefs the tag became 130 chars long, which made it unreadable
    for all program, players and ID3-editors, including TheMPegEncGUI!
    This is now fixed.
    NOTE: This version reads both faulty "130-tags" and correct "128-
    tags" but writes only correct tags so that you can read and rewrite
    all erroneous tags you might have set. Sorry for the inconvenience.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} When starting TheGUI a subprocess is also initiated. The time
    this subprocess has to initiate and respond to the main
    program has been increased as some emulated systems (MorphOS)
    takes longer time to do this. (Especially with a buggy
    AFC tasker-class in TheGUI :(  )

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed a couple of other small bugs and annoyances.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} I have optimized the code a bit so it's between 3-5kB smaller.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} I had missed some parts when I localized. Some :'s was missing
    and there was some other straggly cutted strings.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The "Use filename as title" has been removed from the ID3-Tag
    editor as it's quite useless.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Hungarian catalog slightly updated.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Spanish and Catalonian translations included! Also a
    spanish guide. Traduccin al Espaol por Forkens

@{b}v2.23@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} There was a couple of enforcer hits when TheGUI was started.
    I think I got rid of them. The subprocess creation class
    (AFC) must have a bug in it's stack changing code so instead
    of changing the stack in runtime I hacked the default value
    of the compiled class to be 16kB!

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} When you press Skip in the list window while encoding (or
    playing) the time-counter will now try to calculate how
    long it would have taken to encode the whole song, not
    base it's calculation in the time until you pressed Skip.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The list window's gauge text might have got screwed up when
    the list window was resized. This is harmless but apparently
    the gauge object didn't keep a local copy of the string.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} When ticking the "No ID3's" in the prefs window TheGUI
    crashed. This has been fixed now.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} If you pressed Skip to skip a file when encoding a list and
    the encoder returned an error (like Lame does, it fails 20)
    then the list would have been aborted. This is no long the
    case, no it contain with the next file as expected.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now the prefs are save to ENV: when quitting. So Quit now
    also acts as a "Use" button would have.

@{b}v2.22@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The input/output file strings for Mpega didn't behave right
   Fixed now.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added German and Hungarian (IIRC) catalogs!

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Dieter B was kind to make a HTML-Doc of the guide.

@{b}v2.21@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now TheMPegEncGUI supports the Ogg Vorbis OggEnc encoder!

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now TheMPegEncGUI is finally localized! (translation is
   in progress for german, polish and french)

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added VBR Mode (old/new) to Lame.

@{b}v2.2@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added two new version of TheMPegEncGUI namely:
   TheMPegEncGUI Lite - which only supports Lame and Mpega, and
   TheMpegEncGUI Lame - which only supports Lame!
   Please e-mail me and tell me what you thing of these two
   new versions! Good or bad!

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now the "Approx time left" in the list window also feature
   a gauge! The gauge will show the progress of the current file
   while the time (inside the gauge) will still show the time
   left for the whole list. This also works if you only encode
   one single file, but then you have to open the list window
   yourself.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added some menu options so that you can save custom settings
   allowing for you to configure the program in different ways
   and be able to have all configs saved!

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Removed all code which handled config-files from v1.x including
   loading and prefs-converting code and stupid patches involved
   which reduced the exe by 16kB!

@{b}v2.12@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added 2 options for Lame v3.90+.

@{b}v2.11@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Updated bubble-help and made the Help-key bring up the guide.

@{b}v2.10@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Frequency cycle gadget for Lame gave wrong values.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} It has always been impossible to copy text with RAmiga+c in
   the string gadgets. I now found the problem: The hotkey was
   already used for closing the console output. How stupid.
   This has now been fixed and the output has hotkey 'l'.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} It was impossible to use the extra ID3-options for Lame when
   one was suing a list. Fixed.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added an options to allow long (256 chars) ID3 tag lines as
   Lame can make use of such when writing ID3v2 tags. See the
   preferences for how to enable long ID3 tags.
   TheMPegEncGUI itself can not read or write ID3v2 tags though.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Made a few other fixes here and there..

@{b}v2.09@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added a new page full of settings for Lame.

@{b}v2.08@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added a settable delay between the encoding of files in the
   list to let the filesystem save it's directory structure to
   prevent eventual loss of finished mp3's in case of a crash.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added some modes for Lame.

@{b}v2.07@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added some options for BladeEnc.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Moved the encoder paths to the Prefs making the main
   window a bit smaller.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} A few other smaller changes and fixes.

@{b}v2.06@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The sliders concerning the VBR thing for Lame now each
   have thier own activation checkmark. Appearently some
   of the settings didn't work together..

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The "Use ID3 tag" switch on the Mpega page was irrelevant
   and therefor cause some confusion in the program so I have
   now removed it.

@{b}v2.05@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added the DELETE option for Pegase!

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now TheMPegEncGUI asks you to change the extensions of the
   files in the list if you switch between the Mpega page and
   some encoder page.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} I've added some new options for Lame.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The filepattern was not allways remembers and saved as it
   was supposed to.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed a bug which caused Lame to never write the ID3-track no.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The requesters including the file-requesters, will now always
   open on the same screen TheMPegEncGUI is opened on.
   To make the console open on that same screen too you can add
   /SCREEN PUBSCREENNAME  to the end of the Text Output string.

@{b}v2.04@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added a few simplifying menu-options that you can use when
   setting ID3-tags to your files, wether it will be previously
   encoded files or not.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed a bug with a failure that was never reported if
   an ID3-tag could not be set.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed a bug with the bitrate settings that was saved
   but not used.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed a bug with the output format settings in Mpega
   that was saved but not used.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} If you change the Pattern-field in the file-requester, it will
   now be remembered and saved if you save settings!

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed a bug which made it impossible to save a list with
   ID3-tag with an unknown genre.

@{b}v2.03@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now TheMPegEncGUI is a full featured ID3-tag editor!
   You can now set/edit the ID3-tag of allready encoded files.
   Just flip to the Mpega page and select an input file or
   go to the list and add files. The tagging is done the same
   way as before but with the difference that you don't need
   to encode the files to set the tag!

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed @{b}alot@{ub} of small bugs with the list and the ID3-tagging.
   I can't believe some of the bugs that slipped through!

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now using BetterString.mcc in most stringgadgets!

@{b}v2.02@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} If TheMPegEncGUI always crashed for you it should not do
   so anymore! It was a stack problem. I doubled the stack for
   the sub-process and it worked so I tripled it in this final
   release just for safety!

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now you can set ID3-tags individually for every file, or
   you can set one tag for a group of files and use the filename
   as ID3-Title!

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The progress time report has been improved allot (again) and
   now the time is calculated immediately when you add files
   to the list whether an encoding process is running or not!
   The time factor (encode/play) is also saved when you save
   prefs so that time estimates will be more accurate the next
   time you encode!

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} You can save the list with ID3-tags in textformat and
   maybe edit the file by hand and then reload it!

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The ID3-genres is now sorted :)

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now ID3-tags can be set no matter what encoder you use!
   If you use an encoder that doesn't support ID3-tagging
   TheMPegEncGUI will do the tagging itself!

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} A little bug fixing here and there..

@{b}v2.01@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The progress time report has been rewritten and now
   works quite well I must say!

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} You can now choose what flag(s) you you would like
   to use when sending break to an encoder.
   Before it was just Ctrl-C.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now the application get properly iconified if you
   close every window, before the windows was just hidden.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Included a 147 items long genre list for the encoders
   that support ID3-tagging!

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} TheMPegEncGUI has been tested with Lame v3.70.

@{b}v2.0@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now TheMPegEncGUI is finally in MUI!
   Please give me your suggestions on improvements of the
   layout of this new GUI.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The encoders are now executed completely asynchronous
   and can therefor be interrupted anytime by pressing
   a button in the GUI!

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added a few more options for LAME v3.63 ßeta.

@{b}v1.53@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} TheMPegEncGUI became key-mail ware.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed a bug which caused files to be deleted after they
   where played by Mpega!

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Lame commandline was incomplete! Fixed.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed allot of other bugs. (I haven't had the time to do
   extensive bugtesting for like 8 month!)

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added two "undocumented" switches for Lame.

@{b}v1.52@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The opened/closed state of the console is saved.

 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed the bug with the config which made mostly
   Pegase and BladeEnc to get the wrong settings!

@{b}v1.51@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now you can use the ID3 Tag settings when encoding
   with Lame (v3.50+)!

@{b}v1.50@{ub}
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now supporting BladeEnc!
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} You can open and close the output (console) manually if you want!
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} I have made a little "process manager" to use when
   breaking an encoder or something!  (If someone knows
   how to extract the name out of a CLI process I would
   be glad to hear..!)
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Actual parameters is shown in the GUI!
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} It doesn't specifies default values unless you want it to!
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Ncode is now supported!
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Lame(r) 3 supported!
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} You can have the files saved in the same drawer they
   came from when using the list instead of having all
   files end up in the same drawer!
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} You can set the stacksizes of the encoders!
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} It also supports Mpega for easy play of your encoded files!
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} You can select many files in a list and
   encode them in one stroke!
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} You can have the source-file(s) deleted if you want!
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} You can have date and time written in the output to be
   able to see how long time the file(s) took to compress!
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} You can select output, to send it to KingCON och to a file..!
 @{fg fill}*@{fg text} You can print the commandlines to the encoder if you want
   to compress your files without the GUI!


@endnode

@node encode "Encoders.."

  @{b}Currently supported encoders
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}
* MusicIn   - (68k, PowerUP)
* Pegase    - (68k, WarpOS)
* Ncode     - (68k, PowerUP, WarpOS)
* MP3Enc    - (68k)
* Lame      - (68k, AmigaOS4, MorphOS, PowerUP, WarpOS) -> This is the best encoder!
* BladeEnc  - (68k, PowerUP, WarpOS)
* Flac      - (68k, AmigaOS4, MorphOS)
* OggEnc    - (68k, AmigaOS4, MorphOS)
* ConvertA8 - (open source)

  @{b}Currently supported decoder
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}
* Mpega    - (68k, AmigaOS4, MorphOS, PowerUP, WarpOS)
* OggDec   - (68k, AmigaOS4, MorphOS)
* Faad     - (68k, AmigaOS4)
* Ogg123   - (68k, AmigaOS4, MorphOS)
* PlayA8   - (open source)


  @{b}Where did I find these encoders??
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

  Aminet: http://www.aminet.net/

  OS4Depot: http://www.os4depot.net/

On which systems these encoders actually work am I not quite sure of,
so don't be alarmed if it says (above) that an encoder doesn't work
on a particular system (PowerUP, WarpOS..), cause it might, or might
not..!

If anyone would come up with some other encoder I don't know about
and you want a GUI for it, just tell me where to get it and it
might end up in the next version :-)


@endnode

@node tiptrix "Tips and trix.."

  @{fg shine}@{b}Tips & Trix
  ~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   1. If you want to make the console totally disappear you should
      do it like this:
        Open the prefs window.
        Set Disable encoder output.
        Set Errors through requester.
        Unset Print start and stoptime.

   2. If you want all mp3's you compress to end up in the directory
      where the aiff file (or alike) for each file is:
        Open the prefs window.
        Set Dynamic destination for list.

   3. If something interrupted the wizard while encoding a CD,
        just add the *complete* CD again and process to tag editing.
        CodeAudio will automatically detect that some songs have already
        been encoded and offer not to record them again. But you
        need to add all songs to get the CDDB information correct.

   4. I don't want to use CodeAudio when encoding but I still don't
      want to enter those long commandlines.
        Open the prefs window.
        Set the Text output to a file, like f.ex "RAM:test.txt".
        Then set up your encode list or your file to encode and select
        "Print commandlines" from the Managing menu and voila, you have
        a script in RAM:test.txt which you can execute from shell.

   5. LAME.elf is always crashing.
        Open the prefs window.
        Set the stacksize for Lame to something higher than 100000 byte.
        I use 120000 and have never had a crash.

   6. If an encoder doesn't respond when you press Break/Stop/Skip.
        Open the prefs window.
        Change the Ctrl-break flags. Try setting all of them.
        If this doesn't work, the encoder probably hanged. Try
        increasing the stack for it.

   7. The system becomes very slow when encoding.
        Open the prefs window.
        Set the Encode-pri to something lower than 0, -5 is good.

   8. If you don't want to have the window(s) open when you encode.
        Open the prefs window.
        Set Hide main window when encoding. Otherwise you can always
        close them manually. The Quit button in the main window will
        always become a Hide button when encoding.

   9. How to use CodeAudio as an ID3-tag editor.
        Flip to the Mpega page and load a file, or open the list and
        load many files. If you are not using the list then select
        "Use ID3 Tag" and press "TAG Editor"...
        If you use a list then doubleclick on a files or mark one or
        more files and press "I-Tag" and you will be on your way.

  10. How to ID3-tag a whole album easily.
        Add all files in the album to the list.
        Select all files and press G-Tag. Now all files have the same tag.
        Now set all common strings like Artist, Album, Year etc.
        Then select all files and press I-Tag to get individual tags
        for all files. Now the only thing you have to write is the
        Title, because Artist, Album etc was already set when the files
        were group-tagged.
        You can also use the entries in the ID3-tagging menu if you already
        have useful filenames on your files.

  11. If you want CodeAudio on its own screen you can use the MUI-
        settings to do that. The problem is that the console will not
        automatically follow. You can however make it follow by adding
        /SCREEN PUBSCREENNAME  to the end of the Text Output string
        where PUBSCREENNAME is the name of the pubscreen you moved
        CodeAudio to. Add f.ex  /SCREEN DOPUS.1  if you want the
        console to open on DirOpus' screen.


@endnode

